{"/service/ndnp/rp/batch_rp_froghemoth_ver01/data/sn91070631/00516991665/1908030201/0484.xml":{"full_text":"W rfl|ol-n'u in\nVOL. Ill,\u2014-NO, 53. PROVIDENCE. R. 1., MONDAY. MARCH 2,190 R. EIGHT PAGES. PRICE; ONE CENT.\nFIRE DESTROYS PART\nOF CITY OF TAMPA, FLA.\nTHREE HUNDRED AND EIGHT BUILDINGS. INCLUDING FIVE\nCIGAR FACTORIES AND NUMEROUS RESTAURANTS,\nSALOONS, BOARLING HOUSES AND HOMES BURNED.\nFLAMES SWEPT OVER AREA OF 45 ACRES.\u2014RESIDENTS\nOF DISTRICT PANIC STRICKEN AND ONE WOMAN DIED\nFROM SHOCK.\nTampa, Fla.. March I.\u2014The entire ex\ntreme northeastern section of the city\nwas destroyed by fire between w a. m.\nand 1 p. m. to-day. The area burned\ncovered <5 acres and 308 buildings were\ndestroyed, entailing a loss estimated at\n>600.000.\nThe burned section Included four large\nand one small cigar factories and num\nerous restaurants, saloons, boarding\nhouses and over 3>o dwellings occupied by\nclgnrmakers. The factories burned were\nthose of M. Stachelberg Co., lose 1100,-\n000; M- Perez Co., loss >50.000; Gonzales\nFisher Co., loss MO,000; Esberg, Gun st\nA Co., a branch of the Stachelberg Com\npany, loss >40.000; Fernandez A Brother,\nloss >20.000.\nAll factories carried large stocks af\ntobacco and cigars. Tho area swept by\nfire embraced all that portion of the\ncity between Twelfth and Michigan ave\nnues and Sixteenth and Twentieth\nstreets. It originated In a boarding\nhouse tn Twelfth avenue and fanned by\na strong wind spread out, defying tho\nefforts of the entire city fire department\nwhich was crippled by very weak water\npressure. Occupants of over 200 dwelling\nhouses, thrown into a panic, rushed out.\nattempting to save but little of their be\nlongings. One fatality is reported, a\nCuban woman who dropped dead from\nshock. Her body was rescued from the\nburning house with difficulty.\nAmong the buildings other than fac\ntories destroyed were the hotels and\ncafes of Perez and Castro and Maximo\nCaras The fire finally burned Itself out.\nIn the Stachelberg factory a solid sil\nver case valued at >25.000, tn which cigars\nof the firm were displayed at world\u2019s\nfairs and expositions waa destroyed.\nAt the home of Miguel Rodriguez. a\ncigarmaker, the corpse of a child in a\ncoffin awaiting funeral services was cre\nmated.\nAt Elwood City, Pa.\u2014Loss, ffiO.OOO.\nElwood City. Pa.. March I.\u2014A trans\nformer at the plant of the Elwood Power\nFOI ND DEAD IN RED.\nAndrew Hamilton, Former Counsel\nfor New York Life Insurance o.\nAlbany, N. Y., March I\u2014Andrew Ham\nilton, formerly counsel to the New Ysrk\nJ.ife and other insurance companies and\nin charge for many years of insurance\nlitigation and legislative matters In all\nparts of this country and Canada, was\nfound dead In bed this morning at his\nhome in this city. Yesterday he was\napparently in normal health, although he\nhas been failing f\u00b0 Home extent ever\nsince the death of Mrs. Hamilton last\nJufcy. An autopsy this afternoon dis\nclosed an acute dilation of the heart,\nwhich must have caused practically in\nstantaneous death during the night.\nJudge Hamilton, so called, because he\nwas twice elected Judge of the Albany\nCity Court, was widely known from con\nnection of his name with disclosures re\ngarding political and legislative matters\nduring the insurance Investigation of 19h5.\nHe was abroad at the time, but re\nturned while the Armstrong committee s\nbills were still before the Legislature and\nmade a sensational speech before the\ncommittee. a\nHo vehemently denounced by name the\ndirectors of the New York Life, who,\nhe said, evaded responsibility which be\nlonged to them for acts which had been\ncriticised, and let the stigma rest es\npecially upon himself and upon President\nJohn A. McCall, whose then recent death\nhe attributed largely to the acts of these\ndirectors.\nJudge Hamilton was born in Lanslng\nburg, now part of Tro>y. April 29, 1854.\nHe was formerly District Attorney of Al\nbany county and Clerk of the State Court\nof Claims. During the past 10 er 15 years\nhe was known as an authority upon cor\nporation and insurance law. His most\ncelebrated case, which brought him into\nconfidential connection with the New\nYork Life, was that in which the Court\n\u2022f Appeals sustained his contention that\nthe pension contract of that company\nwith ex-President William H. Beers pro\nviding for a life pension of 937,500 a year,\nwas invalid and against public policy.\nHe was the guilding figure in important\nlitigation for the New York Life and\nother companies in many ether States and\nin Europe.\nJudge Hamilton is survived by his aged\nmother and three daughters.\nMIRAGB BELIEVED RBSFOMRIRL\u00ae.\nReport That Feer Warships Were\nSiKhtedtotr Oabe Not ConHrmed.\nHonolulu, March 1-\u2014 -Concerning a re\nport that four supposed warships han\nbeen sighted off Oahu, nothing was\nlearned to-day. It is now believed that\nthe report arose out of the existence of a\nmirage or peculiar cloud effect.\nnitITIMf PREMIER HAS RKI.AI\u2019SE.\nMap Met Appear In Parliament\nAaaln Thia Session.\nLondon, March I.\u2014Sir Henry Campbell-\nBannerman, the Prime Minister, has suf\nfered a relapse, as a result of seeing peo\nple and transacting business oh Saturday.\nThe attending physicians consider that\nthe weakness sf the heart Is the most\nserious factor In the Premier's illness, be\nwill go to the continent as soon as he Is\nstrong enough and It Is likely that he\nwill reappear In Parliament this session.\nAll exertion and excitement particularly\nare forbidden*\nCompany exploded to-doy and threw\nblazing oil throughout the building. The\nstructure and some valuable machienry\nwas destroyed by the flames, entailing a\nloss estimated at >BO.OOO.\nLOSS IN NEW YORK, g2,ftUh,ooo.\nPires st Car Barns and Paint Fae\nlory Did Mnch Dnmaue.\nNew York, March I.\u2014Two fires that\nbrought out all the fire apparatus in the\nupper section of the city and raged from\nmidnight until dawn to-dav destroyed\nthe car barns of the New York City\nRailway Company in Harlem and the\npaint factory of George W. Grote A Co.,\nonly a few blocks distant. Seven hun\ndred and forty surface cars were burned\nand the loss to the company is estimated\nat >2,500,000. The loss on the paint fac\ntory Is given as >125.000, it was the rail\nway company's second serious fire within\na year, the former having destroyed the\nMadison avenue car barns.\nThe car barns took up the block\nbounded by First and Second avenues\nand Ninety-sixth and Ninety-seventh\nstreets. The firemen fought the flames\nfrom the elevated road and It is con\nsidered remarkable that no one wa H in\njured by the falling walls. The fire\nstarted in a paint shop on the second\nfloor of the barns and within half an\nhour the building was doomed. Motor\nmen succeeded in getting a few rars into\nthe street, but tlje intense heat prevented\nthe saving o f more than a small part of\nthe rolling stock. During the fire the\npolice ordered score a of families, living\nopposite the barns, to leave their tene\nments. Four alarms were turned in for\nthe Are.\nhlle the apparatus was responding to\nthe fourth alarm on the car barn Are\ntwo alarms were turned In for the fire in\nthe Grote A Co. establishment, a four\nstory building on One Hundred and Sec\nond street. The paints end oils blazed\nhm ai* y nn<l W,th n a hert t,f n\u00ab the\nbuilding was in ruins.\nTORPEDO BOATS AT CALLAO.\nflotilla Arrive at Peruvian Fort fn\nGood Condition.\nCallao. March 1.-The American torpedo\nooat flotilla, which left TaJcahuano en\nFob. 25. arrkwd here to-day. The com\nmander of the flotilla, Lieut. 11. I. Cone,\nd< la red that throughout the voyage, 1500\nknote, the weather was fine and condi\ntion*, such that good time to the Peruvian\nP\u00b0 M,ble The dertroyenuarrived\nin splendid condition, not a hitch having\noccurred to mar the passage.\nC ne Wl>eakB highly of the hos\n?bu y rece,ved at the hands of the\nw hXhe Mn<i r aS part,cular ly pleased\nBerv lceg rendered by Lieut.\nommander luizos of the Chilean Naw\ntl e\u00b0in C nor Capac,ty of Pilot through\nS.kl?uan^n S r fnHn Pun,a Arenas\u2019\u2022\ntilla w V r expec, d that the flo-\nIU will remain here until March 9 sail\nln that dat e for Panama.\nr.. nd d\n.h IM W\u2122 bM\nrl>\u00abl ,w.r. put aKlrt th.\ndent Pardo presented to each thfTa'\nPe\u2122 '\u25a0\u201c\u2022'\u2022\u2019\u25a0W bound book\nwomam held ip.\nVi.,.,,. #RJ\nHobbed on L\u2019nlon Avenue.\nye\\\u2122*oM I,aHnn Wonian M\non rmn eld p ~car hPr home\non I nion avenue Saturday night hit on\nthe head and robbed. Yesterday she was\n*wm U cond,tlon It is believed\nS he7lf rt rv en h a y recover According\nto her story, she went to a grocery\non Pocasset avenue and was returning\nL when four men suddenly corn\nfr \u00b0nted her. They demanded her money\nand before she could reply sh o wa, struck\non the head with a club and her bundles\nand the change she carried n her han d\nwjro wrested from her. Tho men made\nThe police of tho Sixth Precinct were\nnot notified until yesterday, and imme\ndiately set about to land the highway\nmen it possible. The woman could give\nno description of the men, but declared\nthey are Italians. declared\nWOK GOLD RACQVKT TITLE.\nJ. (.ordnn l)ongl\u00abi Defeated F, p.\nHolland tn Straight Games.\nTuxedo Park, N. Y., March I.\u2014J. (Jor\ndon Douglas of the New York Racquet\nand Tennis Club won the gold racquet\nchampionship to-day by defeating F. p,\nRolland, amateur racquet champion of\nCanada, in three at might games. The\nprise was a gold racquet presented by\nClarence 11. Mackay.\nDouglas played a fast match and out-*\nplayed Holland, who was favorite. Doug\nlas won the first and second games rather\neasily by the scores of IS to s and 16 to 6.\nrespectively. The third match was\nstubbornly fought, but by careful placing\nDouglas succeeded In capturing the game\nby a score of 18 to 16,\nAN INQUEST WILL\nBE ORDERED\nOFFICIAL INVESTIGATION OF\nFATAL STABBING.\nAffair on Richmond Street Which\nResulted in Death of Lawrence\nMcKiernan Will be Probed to\nthe Bottom. \u2014No Further Evi\ndence Against Mulvey.\nAccording to the police of the Fifth\nPrecinct Station, Michael Mulvey, 3S\nyear old, who was arrested Saturday\nnight in connection with the stabbing af\nfray that resulted in the death of Ij\u00bbw\nrencn McKiernan, 21 years old, of 877\nEddy street, will be arraigned this morn\ning on a charge of manslaughter. Though\nthe police worked all day yesterday on\nthe case, questioning a large number of\nwitnesses, no developments wore found\nI*llo knife which Mulvey Is alleged to\nhave used remains unidentified as belong\ning to him.\nTlie Aght occurred on Richmond street,\nnear South street, at an early hour yes\nterday morning and Is .alleged to have\nstarted ovt a remark passed from a\ncrowd of young fellows standing at the\ncorner to Mulvey and three of his com\npanions as they came down the street\non the opposite tide.\nAn autopsy was performed on the body\nof McKiernan yesterday. It was found\nthat an artery had been severed in the\nabdomen and that he had bled to death\nas he lay in the road near the sidewalk.\nMedical Examiner Perkins, who had\ncharge of the case, has ordered an in\nquest In his report to the Coroner that\nwill probably be begun at once.\nA large crowd of the curious docked\nto the acene of the fatality yesterday af\nternoon. All day yesterday groups gath\nered on the corners and discussed the\ntragedy. It was the sole topic In that\nsection of the city.\nMcKiernan well known.\nThe young man, the victim of the stab\nbing, was well known and had many\nfriends. He was 21 years old and would\nhave been S 3 on the 25th of next month.\nHe is survived by a mother, two brothers,\nJohn F. and Peter W., and a sister,\nKatherine McKiernan. Another sister,\nMary, was killed a little more than a\nyear ago by falling from an electric car\nas she was on the way from Pawtuxet\nto this city.\nJohn F. McKiernan. 28 year* old and\nthe oldest of the family, said last night\nthat his brother had always had a good\nreputation and was an industrious young\nman and a graduate of the Point Street\nGrammar School. The brothers have\nmanaged a, grocery store since the death\nof their father at 222 Richmond street.\nSaturday night, as usual, the store was\nclosed at midnight. John McKiernan was\nthe last tc leave. I4tvrr\u00abnee had\nthere during the evening, but had gone\nout a few minutes before closing time.\nMr. McKiernan said last night that It\nhad been the custom of hla brother and\nsometlmea himself to remain In the vicin\nity until after the closing of the saloons.\nThis was done to see that no depreda\ntions were committed on their property.\nMr. McKiernan said that men coming\nfrom the saloons, of which there are a\nnumber tn that Immediate vicinity, were\nsometimes boisterous and had often\npulled blinds of houses from their fasten\nings. The McKiernan family owns a num\nber of dwelling houses along Richmond\nstreet. And to see that they were not\ndamaged. Mr. McKiernan said, was the\nreason that his brother Lawrence was\nstanding at the corner early yesterday\nmorning.\nStanding close by were other young\nmen. Their names as received by the\npolice are: James Crane of 316 Dyer\nstreet. Frank Doyle of 256 Richmond\nstreet, Arthur Malley of 85 Elm street,\nThomas H. Fitzpatrick of 416 Eddy street,\nThomas and Arthur Bradley of 63 Elm\nstreet, James Kelly of \u00bbio Richmond\nstreet and Alonzo Keroack of 78 Winter\nsttree Mr. McKiernan said that thougn\nbls brother knew these young men he\nwas sure that Lawrence had not been\nwith them.\nSTART OF THE TROUBLE\nThe police say that Mulvey, the man\nunder arrest, with two friends. James\nO'Donnell of 9 Allen's avenue and James\nWinn of 83 Blackstone street, hoth mid\ndlc-nged men. came down the street from\nsome saloon further up, and were on the\nopposite side. As they came even to\nthe crowd on the corner, it Is alleged\nthat a remark was hurled at the three\nmen, with a dare for them to come across.\nMulvey and his two companions, whom\nthe police say had been drinking with\nhhn during the night. Immediately took\nup the quftrrel, and after a sharp pas\nsage at words the three men came across\nthe street. The fight then began.\nThe noise that the men made startled\nthe neighborhood and out of his house\nacross the street rushed Joseph Donovan.\nHe Is alleged to have mingled tn the\nfray and received a cut In his side that\nrequired five stitches to close. Fitzpat\nrick, one of the young men said tor have\nbeen In the ciowd. was also cut and had\nto be taken to the hospital, where 10\nstitches closed the wound.\nAccording to what John McKiernan said\nlast night, his brother had not mingle!\nin the tight. One of the young men In\nthe crowd is said to have seen Lawrence\nMcKiernan go to help a man who had\nfallen to the sidewalk. \u201cMy brother,\"\nsaid Mr. McKiernan, as I heard the\nstory from one of th<\u00bbse there, was try\ning to help the fallen man to his feet.\nAs he did so he received the knife thrust\nand fell out Into the street face down.\nI was in bed when my sister heard the\nnoise and someone outside say, \u2018McKier\nnan Is stabbed.\u2019 Rhe told me to get up\nand go out to find out what had hap\npened. That I did, and when I got to\nthe scene the police were there, I saw\nMulvey standing tn the crowd with a cut\non his nnse. I told Officer Tidd to place\nhim under arrest. I said, \u2019That man\nknows something of this.*\nWinn and O'Donnell were locked up on\ncharges of drunkenness and were ar\nraigned in the police court yesterday\nmorning. Capt. fawrence later allowed\nthem to leave, but they will probably be\n(Coatiased oa Page Twe.)\n\\7tce Admiral-ship as\nSurprise for EsVctns\nWashington, March I.\u2014ln a quiet way\nnaval officials In Washington are endeav\noring to arrange a most agreeable sur\nprise foi Admiral Evans when the battle\nship fleet under his command nails\nthrough tho Golden (late and completes\nthe Pacific cruise. To signalize the Gov\nernment's appreciation of the successful\nconduct of this undertaking. It Is pro\nposed to greet the Rear Admiral with a\ncommission a* Vice Admiral of the\nAmerican Navy. Of course, the success of\nthis undertaking <iei*ends upon Congress,\nbut tAa Pecsbjent nun'done his part hi\nrecommending to that bod/ the re-estab\nlishment of that naval grade. It is not\ndoubted that Congress can be Induced to\nact upon this recommendation In sea\nson to isure the issue of Admiral\nEvans's commission before the comple\ntlon of the present cruise, so that be may\nbear the title of Vice Admiral for the\nfew months between his arrival at San\nTRIBESMEN YIELD\nTO BRITISH\nAFRIDIS SUFFER SEVERELY\nIN CAMPAIGN.\nLord Kitchener's Frontier War in\nIndia Pushed with Vigor to\nSuccess. British Expedition\nUnder Maj. Gen. Willco'ks at\nEnd.\nCalcutta, March 1- The British expedi\ntion under Maj. Gen. Sir James Willcocks,\nwhich has been engaged In the Bazar\nValley in punishing the Zakkakhels,\npowerful trilje of Afridis, lum come to\nan end. The troops have vacated the\nBazar Valley and are expected to reach\nPeshawar soon. More than 300 high\ntribesmen petitioned the British Govern\nment to spare the Zakkakhels, promising\nto punish Die offenders in the recent\nraids, because of which the Government\nsent out its punitive expedition.\nThe tribesmen already have suffered\nseverely, for in a remarkably short cam\npaign they have be\u00abn scattered and\nbroken, their forts have been destroyed\nand many of them have been killed. They\nhave now made the fullest submission\nand Gen. Willcocks lias aoospted the\nterms on behalf of the Government.\nLord Kitchener's frontier war in the\nBazar Valley ag.dnst Lite Zakkakb\u00ab*ls\ntribesmen made rapid progress. The\nBritish force under Maj. Gen. Willcocks\nentered the Zakkakhel country early in\nFebruary and at once became engaged In\nstivere lighting with the tribesmen. The\nexi>editlon numbered about English\nand native troops, with an additional\nbrigade in reserve. The Afridis are one\nof the most warlike tribes of the north\nern part of India, but so determined was\nthe advance of the British that they were\nunable to withstand it.\nGen Willcocks employed up-to-date\nmethods and advanced his troops into the\nenemy's country in open order. In this\nwa> the British were able to do gre.it\ntn the trll\u00bbestnen and to escape at\nall times anything like severe losses.\nRecent dl\u00ab?*t<\u2019hes from the frontier said\nthat the rebellious natives were likely,\nto yield at any time, because of iheir\nheavy casualties, the overwhelming force\nof the British and the refusal of other\ntribes to loin the uprising, which dis\ncouraged the rank and file. than a\nweek after the expedition set out. It suc\nceeded In surprising the Zakkakh<-ls. and\nseizing their strongest position near.\nWalsl. and since then II luis severely i\npunished the insurgents. I\nFrancisco and his retirement from active\nservice.\nThe naval argument In support of the\nproposed re-establishment of the grade\nof Vice Admiral Is strongly re-enforced\nby a comparison made at the Navy De\npartment between the British home fleet,\nengaged in the manoeuvres lust fall (of\nwhich a report han juwb rea<f\u00bb here),\nand the battleship fleet commanded by\nHear Admiral Evans. The figures show\nthat the British fleet, composed of 2H\nbattleships. 15 armored cruisers, nine pro\ntected criihstra .itirf 57 frtrpodn craft, were\ncommanded by one Ndmlral, three Vice\nAdmirals, seven Bear Admirals and one\nCommodore.\nThe American fleet, when It Is fully as\nsembled in Han Francisco harbor, will\nconsist of 19 battleships, right armored\ncruisers, three protected cruisers and a\nlarge number of supply ships, colliers\nand repair ships, nln<\u00ab destroyers and flve\ntorpedo boats, commended by only four\nHear Admirals.\nSTRIKE IS ON AT\nWESTERLY\nSTONE YARDS WILL NOT BE\nOPENED TO DAY.\nMotion for a Reconsideration of\nthe Bill of Prices Failed to Re\nceive Necessary Two-Thirds\nSupport and the Granite Cut\nters Will Press Their Demands.\nThe atone yards about Westerly will be\nstill this morning, and If the expressed\ndetermination of the employers and em\nployes amounts to anything, they are\nlikely to remain so for some time to\ncome.\nA meeting of the local branch of the\nGranite Cutters* National Union was\nheld on Saturday evening and It was\nvoted to adhere to the demands made by\nthem. The matter came up on the mo\ntion for ii reconsideration of the bill of\nprices and was defeated, as the neces\nsary two-thlrds was not cast.\nA telegram was received by the local\nbranch yesterday announcing that ques\ntion ns to whether or not the cutters of\nBarre, Vt., would strike was submitted to\nthem and announce,] that the motion to\nstrike wss carried, 17M) being in favor\nand none against.\nAt a meeting of the Paving Cutters*\nUnion held In the parlors of the Dixon\nHouse Saturday evening It was voted\nwithout a dissenting voice to enter upon\na strike this morning If the demands of\nthe men as expressed In their bill of\nprices were not acceded to. The demand\nin the new bill of prices of the paving\ncutters Is to an increase of |l..\u2019iO per\nthousand blocks.\nThe blacksmiths voted to strike at a\nmeeting held on Saturday evening They\ndemand an Increase from 37L><\u2019 per hour\nto 40c. per hour. It wax also voted to al\nlow the blacksmiths engaged in sharpen\ning for quarryme n to continue at the\nrate as now paid pending a settlement\nwith the manufacturers.\nfITORK 1*44 VISIT ftPAIVft qi EEV.\nInteresting Event Expected 4bn at\nthe End of .Inly.\nMadrid, March I.\u2014lt Is officially an\nnounced that the accouchement of Queen\nVlctoila is expected about the end of\nJuly.\nPARTIAL LIQUIDATION FOR\nGUTS!ANDLNG ACCOUNTS\nThough Temporary Officials of Union Trust Confidently Expect\nThat This Week Will See Release of About All Accounts, Yet\nThere is Being Considered a Plan of Excluding Those Who Do\nNot Release Claims from Benefits of the Original Plan.\nThe receivers\u2019 and thr depositors\u2019 com\nmittens of the Union Trust Company\nImivo every ho|\u00bbe that thia week'* vigorous\nindividual solicitation upon outstanding\nparties will Medirr the release of nearly\n100 per eent. of the accounts. To that en<l.\nstarting io early fids morning, the work\nof getting nt every outstanding account\nwill be pressed hard and not 11 thing left\nundone to have everything by Saturday\nIn rendlneag for an Important conference\nto arrange definite details about reopen\ning the hank.\nBut the temporary officials are by no\nmeans letting their lio|m*n run away with\nthem. It Is said to lie recognised that\nthere might be a big hesitancy on the\npart of the Court to allow the reopening\nof the bank with anything like a million\ndolliira ac< mints outstanding. That Is\nwhy so inui'h effort will be exerted to se\ncure more big releases. In thia connection\na new and very significant phase of the\nsituation has developed.\nFor some time, rather quietly, the re\nceivers and members of the depositors'\ncommittee have been seriously consider\ning the possibilities of a partial liquid i\ntlon. That Is to sax, a liquidation which\nwould affect all those parties who per\nsistent ly hold out against releasing ac\ncounts, and which liquidation would\nthus exclude them from participation in\nthe generally accepted happy solution now\nbeing arranged for \u2019thou* who have re\nleaaed their aceounta It l\u00ab a fact that\nthia matter haa been and la seriously con\nsidered and eminent attorneys have de\ncln red that slch a thing la possible.\nThe Idea nf such a plan an that would\nbe thia. With the releasing of nearly 95\nper cent of claims already and a possi\nbility of an Increase to 97 par cent., there\nthen would be left por cent. On the\nsupposition that that 3 per cent, repre\nsented parties who simply refused to\ncome In under the present proposed plan\nand who thus In effect aske<| for liquida\ntion th-' Idea would be tn give It to them\nDRFAHTMKWT RTOHFA CKW*I*.\nNo Cirent Decrease in Atitnber <f\nEmployes is Deported.\nAlthough Col. Webb, the Commissioner\nof Industrial Statistics, who Is acting\nunder directions of the Assembly to get\nat the real facts concerning the unem\nployed In this State, hasn't begun to re\nceive many reports from his investiga\ntions as yet. still, he announced yester\nday, reports from about all the local de\npartment ami grocery stores show that\nthere Is but Utile difference In the num\nber employed now as compared with Last\nyear nt the same period.\n\"Of course. It Is not proper to base\nany judgment upon such few returns,\"\nhe Mid yesterday, \"as the returns to\ndate do not cover the field which la per\ntaps the more greatly affected, that is,\nthe manufacturing establishments. I\nshould *>y in relation to the department\nand grocery stores, however, that the re-\nturns about balance one another as com\npared with last year. I expect to got my\nbest results from the police canvass of\nthe cities and that that part of the work\nwill bo thorough, I think, is assured, for\nthe ]M\u00bbllce of each of the flve cities have\nguaranteed to do the work carefully.\u201d\nIn this connection Col. Webb will prob\nably have ready for distribution among\ntho policemen to-day the slips or blanks\nRAILROADS WILL COMPLY\nWITH \u201cNINE-HOUR LAW\u201d\nSeveral Thousand Additional Operators and the Closing of a\na Large Number of Small Railroad Stations Will be Neces\nsary When Law Becomes Effective on March 4. It is Claimed.\nOfficials, However, Anticipa\nWashington. March I.\u2014American rail\nways have arranged to comply with the\n\"nine-hour law.\u201d The operation of the\nlaw will mean the employment by rail\nroad companies of several thousand ad\nditions] operators and tho closing of a\nlarge number of small stations on March\n4. The discontinuance of railway ser\nvice at many points. It Is said, will cause\nat least temporary Inconvenience to the\ntravelling and shipping public, but, to re\nduce operating expenses, which now\nseems necessary, the operating officials of\nthe railways believe that thia is the only\nway they possibly can meet the situa\ntion with which they are confronted.\nDuring to heating of applications for\nan extension of the law by the Inter-\nState Commerce Commission, some as\ntonishing statements were made by the\noperating offV lais of important railways.\nA good many lines, owing to a reduction\nIn their revenues and to their inability to\nCommand the cash necessary to meet\ntheir payrolls, have been forced, during\nthe past four months, Almost to the point\nof asking for receivers. In the opinion\nof railway officials expressed at the hear\ning under oath and In private conversa\ntion this condition does not seem to'have\nbeen due to the enforcement of regula\ntive laws or to the incapacity of railway\nmanagement. Most of the off) lais at\ntribute the difficulty to the unfortunate\nbanking situation which developed last\nSeptember.\nBut not a single official of a single\nrailway line who appeared before the\nCommission, expressed the belief that\nthe present industrial depression would\n\u2022If rotiree It In eald tn b<> recognised hv\nthe receiver* that auch out\u00df\u2019andlng par*\ntie* would not no much care for liquida\ntion after all, an they would imagine that\nthe hank would not be opened anyway\nand thua they will be allowed to with\ndrew their Halma Juat as thoee who have\nentered Into the contract to accept the\neliding acale agreement.\nNow, under much condition*, It la held\nby good legal authority, that It would be\npOKnlble, with precedent In equity for ao\ndoing, to aet aalde aay aome 8 per cent,\nof the HRaeta of the company and almply\nan/ to out\u00dftnndlng partlea; '*Oo ahead\nun<l have your liquidation, ai