orms and bllszards and railway\nand telegraphic communication is inter\nrupt d in many places. In parts of Scot\nland the snowdrifts are 10 and 15 feet\nd\u00bb***p. It Is expected that the railways\nwill be blocked for a considerable length\nof time because equipment for clearing\nthe tracks of such obstruction Is lack\ning.\nA passenger train was stalled between\nGlasgow and Fort Williams all last\nnight and relief trains wore unable to\nreach It for 27 hours. Mnanwhile the\npassengers were without food.\n:e Return of Prosperous Times.\nlast. They practically uniformly ex*\npressed confidence that the return of\nprosperity would be almost as sudden as\nwa\u00ab the oomlng of adversity and in their\narguments about the enforcement of the\nnine-hour Jaw they told the '\u2019ommlsalen\nthat such a return of prosperity might\nseriously embarrass them in complying\nwith the law because it would render It\ndifficult to commnnd the services of com\npetent operators In sufficient numbers to\nmeet the needs of prosperous conditions.\nWith four or flve exceptions, no impor\ntant railroads In the country have Indi\ncated an Intention to reduce the wages\nof their employes. As Chairman Knapp\nof the Inter-State Commerce Commis\nsion expressed It: \u201d8o far as I am in\nformed, there Is no concerted action on\nthe part of the American railway com\npunles to reduce wnges. Instances of an\nIntention to change the scale of wages\nhave been given, but they can be said to\nbe In no sense general.\"\nSuch railroad companies or their em\nployes as may take advantage of the\nKrdtnan act to obtain the mediation of\nthe Chairman of the Inter-State Com\nmerce Commission and the Commission\ners of will be accorded every op\nportunity fairly to present their case to\nthe Government officials It will be tho\neffort of Chairman Knapp and Prof.\nNeill amicably to adjust the difference*\nbetween the companies and their em\nploye* But their efforts will be purely\nconciliatory and any decisio